&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by the [bold]National Housing Federation[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]              
[normal]We support the 
[normal]concept of 
[normal]Universal Credit and 
[normal]its 
[normal]potential 
[normal]to
[normal] ensur
[normal]e
[normal] that people are better off in work by reducing benefit withdrawal rates. 
[normal]However, 
[normal]the 
[normal]National Housing 
[normal]Federation has several concerns 
[normal]regarding the reforms
[normal], primarily because households do not have a genuine choice to have the housing element of 
[normal]U
[normal]niversa
[normal]l 
[normal]C
[normal]redit paid directly to their landlord. Many tenants would elect to do this to avoid going into 
[normal]arrears
[normal]. We are also concerned that the 
[normal]cumulative impact of 
[normal]benefit cuts 
[normal]means that households 
[normal]increasingly 
[normal]cannot afford 
[normal]to 
[normal]cover the most basic costs of 
[normal]feeding their family
[normal], 
[normal]keeping their home warm
[normal] and paying their rent at the same time
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]              
[normal]Our response focuses on the case for abolishing the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Our recent ComRes poll shows that public opinion is shifting against the social 
[normal]sec
[normal]tor 
[normal]size criteria with 59% in support of Bedroom Tax repeal, up from 51% in April
[normal]. In addition, 87% agree that those who need a spare room for sick or disabled family members should be exempt from the policy. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]              
[normal]We also outline a number of 
[normal]measures tha
[normal]t 
[normal]w
[normal]ould 
[normal]ensure the 
[normal]roll out of Universal Credit 
[normal]reduces the risk of tenants going into 
[normal]debt 
[normal]and protects social 
[normal]landlord
[normal]s’ revenue streams
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]To ensure we have information on the
[normal] long-term
[normal] impact of 
[normal]the Government’s welfare reforms
[normal], the Federation 
[normal]has 
[normal]commissioned Ipsos MORI to survey housing associations in autumn 2013 with a large scale tenants’ survey in 
[normal]early 
[normal]2014. 
[normal]We would be happy to share the 
[normal]results with the Committee in due course. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2[bold]              [bold]The best way to get [bold]the [bold]housing benefit bill down[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]rise in the housing benefit bill
[normal] in recent years
[normal] is a result of higher unemployment, stagnating 
[normal]low 
[normal]wages and rising rent levels in the private rented sector. The consequence is that, of every £1 of government expenditure on housing, 95p is spent on housin
[normal]g benefit and only 5p on building new homes
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: the 
[normal]most effective way of redressing the balance and reducing the housing benefit bill is 
[normal]to 
[normal]build more affordable homes. Government investment in new affordable homes not only helps tackl
[normal]e
[normal] 
[normal]our growing housing crisis, but also has a fundamental role to play in:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3[bold]              [bold]Impact o[bold]f welfare [bold]reform o[bold]n rent arrears [bold]and empty homes[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]In 
[normal]autumn
[normal] 2012, 84% of housing associations believed that their rent arrears would increase 
[normal]as a direct result of 
[normal]the 
[normal]welfare changes
[normal] (taking into account direct payments, 
[normal]the social size criteria and the benefit
[normal] cap)
[normal]. The average increase 
[normal]in arrears 
[normal]expected was 51%
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]At the end of 2012, 
[normal]housing association arrears stood at 5.1% (£572m)
[normal]. If a 51% increase in arrears was realised
[normal] across the sector
[normal], actual arrears levels would rise to 7.7% (totalling £865m).
[normal] 
[normal]This loss in revenue translates into a loss of financial capacity within housing associations to manage and maintain their properties
[normal]; 
[normal]deliver wider community services and build new homes. If all these losses were 
[normal]diverted away from 
[normal]financing new homes, the country would see 17,480 less affordable homes built in a year. 
[normal]Any impact 
[normal]on h
[normal]ouse b
[normal]uilding 
[normal]may be more 
[normal]likely to
[normal] 
[normal]be felt 
[normal]in the next Spending Review period, as 61% of associations
[normal] 
[normal]did not think welfare reform 
[normal]would m
[normal]ake it harder
[normal] to deliver on their commitments under the existing Affordable Homes Programme
[normal]. Though 26% say it 
[normal]would to 
[normal]a fair amount or great deal
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3
[normal]              
[normal]The impact on tenants and communities would also be significant. For individual working-age tenants on housing be
[normal]nefit, th
[normal]e predicted 
[normal]impact 
[normal]would mean outstanding arrears increasing by £250 (up from £492) to £743 on average
[normal] by year end
[normal]. 
[normal]Policis
[normal], in a separate study for the Federation, 
[normal]found that 
[normal]50% of social housing tenants were not confident they would be able to keep up rental payments with a switch to monthly payments in arrears within a Universal Credit. 
[normal]Policis 
[normal]identified 
[normal]families with children, 
[normal]those who 
[normal]juggled their finances through 
[normal]weekl
[normal]y cash budgeting and were already under financial stress
[normal] as most at risk in this move
[normal]. 
[normal]Policis 
[normal]also 
[normal]found that 
[normal]32% of social housing tenants had problematic credit use and it was amongst this group that rent arrears were already concentrated
[normal] and risks to b
[normal]e foun
[normal]d
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: 
[normal]that households are given a genuine choice to have their 
[normal]housing element of Universal Credit 
[normal]paid direct to their landlord
[normal] given the level of risk to rent arrears
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: 
[normal]w
[normal]e 
[normal]welcome the measures the DWP are trialling in the North West pathfinder areas to identify tenants who are vulnerable and at risk of arrears who will 
[normal]have 
[normal]the opportunity to have direct payments to their landlords
[normal]. However, 
[normal]we 
[normal]recommend that the DWP
[normal] 
[normal]accept 
[normal]individual referrals 
[normal]from housing associations as to whom should be placed
[normal] on 
[normal]direct payments from the outset
[normal],
[normal] or when fall
[normal]ing
[normal] into rent arrears
[normal] before the arrears trigger comes into play and gives effect to this
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]              
[normal]I
[normal]n autumn 2012, 
[normal]82% of associations expected the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria to result in a fall of rental income. Our snapshot survey of 
[normal]51
[normal] associations suggests this has been born out, as by the end of June 2013, 71% of them were reporting that their rent arrears levels
[normal] had gone up
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]his took place when Universal Credit had reached only a handful of tenants in the North West so could not be said to be a contributing factor. 
[normal]In 
[normal]the first three months to the end of June
[normal]: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.7
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]first three months 
[normal]does not necessarily 
[normal]indicat
[normal]e 
[normal]what might happen 
[normal]over 
[normal]the 
[normal]longer-
[normal]t
[normal]erm
[normal]. 
[normal]Some households 
[normal]may 
[normal]get deeper 
[normal]into arrears as they find it difficult to make up the shortfall in their rent week after week, or because D
[normal]iscretionary Housing Payments 
[normal](DHP) 
[normal]awarded for a short time c
[normal]ome 
[normal]to an end. Some households may find ways of meeting the extra call on their budgets, by cutting back on expenditure, or boosting their income, for example by taking in lodgers or increasing the number of hours they work. 
[normal]However
[normal], no
[normal]t all
[normal] of these options a
[normal]re 
[normal]open to 
[normal]every household. 
[normal]T
[normal]he Local Government Association 
[normal]has found that
[normal] people’s ability to move or find work to mitigate the impact of welfare reform is constrained by local housing and job markets
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8
[normal]              
[normal]The impact on rent arrears may be limited by 
[normal]people 
[normal]downsizing
[normal], but landlords will suffer 
[normal]a loss in 
[normal]rental income 
[normal]whilst they wait for 
[normal]new tenants 
[normal]to move in
[normal]to empty properties. O
[normal]n 
[normal]average
[normal] -
[normal] before the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria came in
[normal] -
[normal] 
[normal]properties remain
[normal]ed
[normal] vacant for 14 
[normal]d
[normal]ays
[normal]. 
[normal]However, 
[normal]some landlords are reporting that they 
[normal]are finding it difficult to 
[normal]le
[normal]t
[normal] larger family homes due to the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria
[normal],
[normal] resulting not only in an extended 
[normal]period of 
[normal]rental 
[normal]income 
[normal]loss
[normal], 
[normal]but also a waste of a home that a family 
[normal]w
[normal]ould welcome. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4[bold]              [bold]Impact o[bold]f welfare reform on [bold]housing association[bold]s[bold]’[bold] [bold]costs[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]Housing associations are changing their rent collection and arrears management systems in the face of welfare reform and providing additional support for tenants
[normal]. Both have 
[normal]a cost. In autumn 2012
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]F
[normal]or the 60 
[normal]largest associations (representing 49
[normal]% 
[normal]of properties in the sector) the average predicted additional spend up to 2013 was £193,000
[normal]. This is
[normal] expected to rise to over £456,000 
[normal]in 
[normal]2013-14. This suggests for just the largest associations taken together
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]there 
[normal]will be around
[normal] £30 million 
[normal]of 
[normal]additional costs in 
[normal]the first year
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]S
[normal]ome of the costs of investing in new management systems and ways of working will be 
[normal]greater
[normal] 
[normal]in the earlier years. 
[normal]A
[normal]ssociations 
[normal]may
[normal] 
[normal]also 
[normal]adjust the
[normal]ir
[normal] expenditure plans upwards as the i
[normal]mpact of the 
[normal]social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria 
[normal]and new payment arrangements via Universal Credit unfold. 
[normal]While
[normal] it is not possible to predict how 
[normal]this will 
[normal]pan out
[normal], 
[normal]it 
[normal]is safe to
[normal] say 
[normal]that this will take resources away from services and new homes delivery as illus
[normal]trated above in connection with increasing rent arrears levels.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: 
[normal]DWP agrees to
[normal] 
[normal]data sharing arrangements 
[normal]f
[normal]or the housing association sector to ensure that arrangements are put in place to 
[normal]reduce fraud, errors and administrative costs.
[normal] 
[normal]For example
[normal], to ensure the 
[normal]DWP 
[normal]has 
[normal]timely 
[normal]information on changes in rent levels and that associations have information on who is moving onto Universal Credit and in and out of direct payment to their landlord
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: that the DWP work
[normal]s
[normal] in p
[normal]artnership with housing associations, as well as local authorities, 
[normal]to put
[normal] in place local support service frameworks to ensure claimants have ready access to financial inclusion and other services to support them through their claim 
[normal]as
[normal] needed.  
