[normal]5[bold]              [bold]Support[bold]ed housing[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]Universal Credit rules and payment model is unsuitable for people living in short
[normal]-
[normal]term supported housing
[normal],
[normal] such as a homeless hostels
[normal]. The 
[normal]Government is to make proposals for alternative arrangements for exempted 
[normal]supported housing
[normal],
[normal] having
[normal] stress
[normal]ed 
[normal]it is not a cost 
[normal]cutting exercise. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: the 
[normal]supported housing 
[normal]definition 
[normal]must be fit for purpose to ensure that the right people are exempted from claiming housing costs through Universal Credit and directed towards the al
[normal]ternative system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]Recommendation: any new system for determining support for housing costs for people in supported housing 
[normal]should 
[normal]retain the principle of nationally set 
[normal]entitlement and be piloted
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6[bold]              [bold]Impact [bold]of the social [bold]sector [bold]size criteria [bold]on [bold]people’s [bold]wellbeing[bold] and [bold]public services[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.1
[normal]              
[normal]On average, t
[normal]he social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria will reduce the housing benefit payments of 660,000 people by 
[normal]£728 per year
[normal]. 
[normal]Many
[normal] individuals are
[normal] already
[normal] reporting that they are finding it extremely hard to cope with 
[normal]the 
[normal]e
[normal]ffects
[normal]. In their survey of
[normal] social housing tenants in 2012
[normal] Policis found:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal]              
[normal]Having to make up the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria shortfall in the rent and make contributions to council tax will add to financial pressures
[normal] on
[normal] households
[normal]. Th
[normal]is 
[normal]will take 
[normal]its 
[normal]toll on 
[normal]people
[normal]’s wellbeing 
[normal]and 
[normal]could 
[normal]lead 
[normal]to greater demands on public services
[normal] 
[normal]as 
[normal]people
[normal]: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3
[normal]              
[normal]An estimated
[normal] 100,000 
[normal]British 
[normal]households 
[normal]living in social 
[normal]housing 
[normal]with aids and adaptations are also
[normal] 
[normal]affected by the 
[normal]social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria
[normal]. It is likely that many of 
[normal]them 
[normal]would seek their re-provision if they had to mo
[normal]ve
[normal]. Sometimes it will be possib
[normal]le to move existing adaptation
[normal]s. O
[normal]n other occasions new ones will need to be specified and fitted to match the design of the new home. In either scenario there are costs involved 
[normal]including
[normal] assessments by occupational therapists
[normal],
[normal] the labour for removing or fitting the 
[normal]aids and adaptatio
[normal]ns
[normal] and 
[normal]the costs of the equipment. Existing adaptations may become redundant 
[normal]if 
[normal]it is not appropriate for them to be moved, or left for the incoming tenant. This represents a waste of historical investment and an environmental cost. The costs of re-providi
[normal]ng aids and adaptations represents an extra demand on the disabled facility grant (DFG) budgets of local authorities who have duties to assess the needs of disabled people and to meet the costs of appropriate facilities irrespective of their tenure
[normal]. 
[normal]The a
[normal]verage DFG award is £6,500
[normal]. 
[normal]In turn, this puts pressure on central government which allocates funding to local authorities for DFG. 
[normal]H
[normal]ousing associations 
[normal]aim
[normal] to offer people a move to a home which has been built, or already adapted for 
[normal]their 
[normal]needs. However, because of the limited supply of smaller properties this is far from possible in many cases. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4
[normal]              
[normal]The cost to the tax
[normal]-
[normal]pa
[normal]y
[normal]er is not the only factor to consider. 
[normal]Many households affected will find it
[normal] difficult to find a suitable property to move to, or may face additional stresses in trying to co-ordinate moving with the successful and timely re-provision of aids and adaptions. 
[normal]Many will have to choose
[normal] between 
[normal]making up
[normal] the shortfall in their rent
[normal] whi
[normal]ch would
[normal] 
[normal]reduce their weekly household budget
[normal], 
[normal]and
[normal] moving to a less suitable property 
[normal]which would put
[normal] limitations on going about their daily lives. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5
[normal]              
[normal]Government spokespeople repeatedly refer to DHPs as ameliorating the effect of changes to housing bene
[normal]fit, including the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria
[normal]. [bold]D
[normal]uring the passage of the Welfare Reform Act, Lord Freud allocated an additional £30 million to DHP for 2013/14 because of the 
[normal]social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria
[normal],
[normal] aimed at disabled people living in significantly adapted properties and foster carers. 
[normal]The Government 
[normal]also 
[normal]allocated an additional £35 million in year for 2013/14 to ameliorate the impact of the 
[normal]social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria
[normal]. 
[normal]This is 
[normal]part of a wider allocat
[normal]ion for 2013/14 which is now up to £190 million against allocations for previous years of £20m. 
[normal]Though this falls well short of the £480 million savings 
[normal]in the first year 
[normal]the DWP predicts tenants affected by the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria will make up in 
[normal]rental payments
[normal], it 
[normal]is still an additional cost to the tax payer. 
[normal]In addition, 
[normal]an administrative error in the allocations to Scotland has resulted in the Government spending a further £800,000
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.6
[normal]              
[normal]It is entirely possible that the Government will continue to allocate further funds to the DHP 
[normal]pot 
[normal]as the 
[normal]impacts unfold
[normal]. However, individual household
[normal]s
[normal] can
[normal]not
[normal] rely on DHP payments 
[normal]and 
[normal]local authorities have to make very difficult decisions on how to ratio
[normal]n their pot 
[normal]over the
[normal] year
[normal] 
[normal]across 
[normal]people
[normal] in 
[normal]properties owned by private landlords, local authorities and housing associations. Federation research shows that only 21% of local authority DHP awards from April 2013 to end of June 2013 were for six months or 
[normal]longer
[normal].
