[normal]7[bold]              [bold]Does the social [bold]sector [bold]size criteria meet its [bold]own [bold]policy objectives?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Impact on savings[bold]7.1
[normal]              
[normal]The Government claims that the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria will 
[normal]save
[normal] 
[normal]the tax
[normal]-
[normal]payer 
[normal]£480 million
[normal] 
[normal]in its first year
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Whether or not this is realised depends on the extent to which people downsize into the more expensive private rented sector and who subsequently moves into their 
[normal]vacated 
[normal]home. 
[normal]Riverside, Affinity Sutton, Gentoo and Wigan and 
[normal]Leigh Housing
[normal],
[normal] with support fr
[normal]om the Centre for Housing Policy University of York
[normal],
[normal] have run their own data through the DWP’s 
[normal]cost 
[normal]impact model and this suggests that the savings may be considerably less than 
[normal]a
[normal]ssumed 
[normal]by the DWP. 
[normal]Their modelling is based 
[normal]on their 
[normal]observed level of moves 
[normal]by tenants affected by the social 
[normal]sector 
[normal]size criteria into the private rented sector
[normal]. 
[normal]Anal
[normal]ysis from the Federation shows 
[normal]that
[normal] families under-occupying two bedroom homes who move to a one-bed flat in the private rented sector would end up claiming an aver
[normal]age of £1,500 more per year in housing benefit – even though they’ll be living in smaller properties
[normal].
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2
[normal]              
[normal]The Government’s projected savings also 
[normal]fail to take into 
[normal]account 
[normal]the 
[normal]subsequent
[normal] costs to public services 
[normal]and the 
[normal]costs incurred by landlords 
[normal]as 
[normal]explored above
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
